WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:18.080
So, when we are starting out in data science within an organization, within a larger organization,

00:00:18.080 --> 00:00:21.000
usually there's the first one.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:25.320
And the first one is doing all of the things.

00:00:25.320 --> 00:00:29.240
And just because a data scientist can do all of the things doesn't necessarily mean that

00:00:29.240 --> 00:00:32.480
a data scientist should do all of the things.

00:00:32.480 --> 00:00:33.480
But it's fine.

00:00:33.480 --> 00:00:36.480
It's fine because it's where a lot of serendipity comes from.

00:00:36.480 --> 00:00:39.599
It's a lot of where innovation comes from.

00:00:39.599 --> 00:00:43.119
So there's nothing wrong with being the first one, with being the only one, with being the

00:00:43.119 --> 00:00:44.959
only one for years.

00:00:44.959 --> 00:00:51.560
But A, that only works as long as the product that your company is making money from is

00:00:51.560 --> 00:00:57.520
not data scientific, because otherwise there really should be a whole team doing this.

00:00:57.520 --> 00:01:05.120
But it's also because as more information is acquired, as more analyses are performed,

00:01:05.120 --> 00:01:07.959
there's greater knowledge that can be applied.

00:01:07.959 --> 00:01:11.199
And so it makes sense to start expanding on that team.

00:01:11.199 --> 00:01:14.480
And so what I'm going to talk about is how do you do that.

00:01:14.480 --> 00:01:18.760
The thing that happens a lot when you have a single person doing all the things is you

00:01:18.760 --> 00:01:22.959
start having not just tech debt, but you start having foundational tech debt.

00:01:22.959 --> 00:01:30.040
You start having rickety, duct-taped systems put together that suddenly start having to

00:01:30.040 --> 00:01:36.480
have resilience tacked on top of, rather than thought through initially.

00:01:36.480 --> 00:01:42.360
And so one of the things that tends to take place in an organization when you reach this

00:01:42.360 --> 00:01:48.519
point is that you have to take things offline in order to start fresh, or you have to refactor

00:01:48.680 --> 00:01:57.080
things while they're burning to steal the animated GIF that JD had earlier with the

00:01:57.080 --> 00:01:59.760
weight lifter in the middle of the fire.

00:01:59.760 --> 00:02:02.120
And that's very true.

00:02:02.120 --> 00:02:07.639
What you don't want to do is reach that point where you have to take your entire system

00:02:07.639 --> 00:02:13.199
offline for, God forbid, days, but even hours, so that you can fix all of these duct taping

00:02:13.199 --> 00:02:18.500
that has taken place, because the data scientist whose role really should be analyzing information

00:02:18.500 --> 00:02:21.899
and communicating that information, iterating on that information, and coming up with novel

00:02:21.899 --> 00:02:26.940
solutions to problems, what they're doing is they're building structures, and a lot

00:02:26.940 --> 00:02:31.899
of the times data science and data engineering become synonymous when they really aren't.

00:02:31.899 --> 00:02:35.580
They're different skill sets that a team needs to have.

00:02:35.580 --> 00:02:37.339
And so when do you grow?

00:02:37.339 --> 00:02:42.339
If you're the only data scientist in a team, when do you tell other people with hiring

00:02:42.339 --> 00:02:45.699
budgets that you need help, and how do you convince them?

00:02:45.699 --> 00:02:48.179
There's three things that are telltale signs.

00:02:48.179 --> 00:02:53.220
The first one is scope, when there's too much to do for one area of expertise or for one

00:02:53.220 --> 00:02:54.660
pair of hands.

00:02:54.660 --> 00:03:00.220
When you've reached a level of maturity that it makes sense to introduce additional expertise

00:03:00.220 --> 00:03:03.660
into the team, and also to increase speed.

00:03:03.660 --> 00:03:05.820
And here's the kicker.

00:03:05.820 --> 00:03:08.820
The last one doesn't happen.

00:03:08.820 --> 00:03:13.380
Every time you add people to an organization, you add complexity.

00:03:13.380 --> 00:03:18.259
And when you add complexity, what you're actually doing is you are improving your ability

00:03:18.259 --> 00:03:23.500
to handle an expanded scope, you are improving your ability to mature as an organization,

00:03:23.500 --> 00:03:26.259
and you are by definition slowing down.

00:03:26.259 --> 00:03:33.380
So unless you are increasing the quality of your underlying systems just by adding humans,

00:03:33.380 --> 00:03:35.020
you're actually not going to solve your problem.

00:03:35.020 --> 00:03:38.460
So as you're thinking about expanding a team and working together as a team, you have to

00:03:38.460 --> 00:03:47.220
realize that as hard as it is to use sophisticated data analytical tools to reach conclusions,

00:03:47.220 --> 00:03:52.660
getting humans to work together is at the very least no easier.

00:03:52.660 --> 00:03:53.860
So how do you do it?

00:03:53.860 --> 00:03:59.460
How do you get to a point where you're not being penalized velocity-wise by having an

00:03:59.460 --> 00:04:01.020
expanded team?

00:04:01.020 --> 00:04:02.020
You do three things.

00:04:02.020 --> 00:04:04.860
You add specialization, you add process, and you add resilience.

00:04:04.860 --> 00:04:06.179
So what do I mean by that?

00:04:06.179 --> 00:04:09.419
By adding specialization, I mean that you want to have different people doing different

00:04:09.419 --> 00:04:13.179
things and doing the things that spark joy.

00:04:13.179 --> 00:04:16.880
So you want data scientists sciencing on data.

00:04:16.880 --> 00:04:22.519
You want data analysts building analytical pipelines that are going to be monitoring

00:04:22.519 --> 00:04:23.519
your systems.

00:04:23.519 --> 00:04:27.660
You want data engineers to do the data engineering and to lay down the foundations that you're

00:04:27.660 --> 00:04:29.920
going to be using in your analysis.

00:04:29.920 --> 00:04:37.519
You want to increase the presence of operations talent, which is undervalued as far as I'm

00:04:37.519 --> 00:04:44.559
concerned, but incredibly important for smart organizations.

00:04:44.559 --> 00:04:48.239
And you want to have somebody who really truly understands the product, the financials.

00:04:48.239 --> 00:04:49.760
What is the pain point of the customer?

00:04:49.760 --> 00:04:52.079
What is the journey that that customer is going through?

00:04:52.079 --> 00:04:56.160
Whoever that customer may be, whether that customer is an end user who is actually walking

00:04:56.160 --> 00:05:02.000
into a store and buying your product or whether that customer is a taxpayer and your product

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:06.880
is IRS-like, one would hope.

00:05:06.880 --> 00:05:09.320
The other thing that you can do is you add process.

00:05:09.320 --> 00:05:13.279
So this is something that I harp on quite a bit.

00:05:13.279 --> 00:05:14.839
Have a documentation party.

00:05:14.839 --> 00:05:23.279
Take a day, move everybody to an offsite location so that they don't get distracted, and provide

00:05:23.279 --> 00:05:29.160
pizza or pastries or any other kind of healthier options.

00:05:29.160 --> 00:05:34.600
And get together to explain what it is that has been going on.

00:05:34.600 --> 00:05:37.440
It's a lot easier when you have everybody in a room going, like, what was the context

00:05:37.440 --> 00:05:38.440
of that?

00:05:38.440 --> 00:05:39.440
What were we thinking about?

00:05:39.440 --> 00:05:40.720
Why did that decision get made?

00:05:40.720 --> 00:05:42.859
What were the constraints that we were operating under?

00:05:42.859 --> 00:05:50.359
Because one thing that happens quite a bit is there's a lot of judgment that happens

00:05:50.359 --> 00:05:54.320
after the fact, where somebody will go, why didn't they just do this?

00:05:54.320 --> 00:06:00.200
Or why the heck would anybody have done this in way A instead of way B?

00:06:00.200 --> 00:06:04.839
And the reason usually is very sensible, because we are all very smart nerds, all different

00:06:04.839 --> 00:06:05.839
kinds of nerds.

00:06:05.839 --> 00:06:09.299
But we tend to be smart nerds, and we don't do things for stupid reasons.

00:06:09.299 --> 00:06:14.760
So document those reasons so that you know how to modify those processes to fit the purpose

00:06:14.760 --> 00:06:16.459
as that purpose evolves.

00:06:16.459 --> 00:06:22.660
Things like authentication, things like governance, provenance is also really important.

00:06:22.660 --> 00:06:30.420
So as your data traverses through a system and gets manipulated, modified, and used in

00:06:30.420 --> 00:06:35.839
different ways, you want to add information, metadata, about that data as it goes through,

00:06:35.839 --> 00:06:40.980
so that you use the correct piece of data at the correct point in the pipe for the reasons

00:06:40.980 --> 00:06:42.540
that you need.

00:06:42.540 --> 00:06:43.540
And also automation.

00:06:43.619 --> 00:06:49.540
I mean, I think JD also said it earlier, and I can't underscore it enough.

00:06:49.540 --> 00:06:52.820
Whenever humans touch data, they breed errors.

00:06:52.820 --> 00:06:56.220
They introduce confusion.

00:06:56.220 --> 00:07:00.899
And automation is great at catching those things.

00:07:00.899 --> 00:07:04.059
Automation is not great at many things, but this is one of the things that you really

00:07:04.059 --> 00:07:05.940
want to leverage it for.

00:07:05.940 --> 00:07:09.100
And then the third step is adding resilience.

00:07:09.100 --> 00:07:13.119
So have a well-thought-through hiring process.

00:07:13.700 --> 00:07:19.040
This is literally one of the most important things that you can do as both a team member

00:07:19.040 --> 00:07:23.760
and a team manager, is making sure that the people that you are hiring to work with you

00:07:23.760 --> 00:07:29.200
or that you are convincing to work with you in your volunteer endeavors, you don't want

00:07:29.200 --> 00:07:31.160
friends.

00:07:31.160 --> 00:07:35.440
You want people who could be friends with you, but the example that I have is I have

00:07:35.440 --> 00:07:41.839
somebody that I have worked with for years now, and upon meeting him, I recoiled.

00:07:41.839 --> 00:07:42.839
I was like, why?

00:07:42.839 --> 00:07:44.720
Who chose to hire this person?

00:07:44.720 --> 00:07:47.000
Are they out of their mind?

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:53.880
Because A, I wasn't mature enough to understand the value of what I'm about to say, but also

00:07:53.880 --> 00:07:59.279
because I think that person would never have hired me, because we have very different personalities.

00:07:59.279 --> 00:08:05.279
But what we have is a drive to do our jobs and to do it well.

00:08:05.279 --> 00:08:11.040
All of the different ways that we clash come from a very good place, and we are now able

00:08:11.239 --> 00:08:16.959
to understand that any kind of conflict that arises is not a conflict of character, but

00:08:16.959 --> 00:08:20.359
it's a conflict of understanding or a conflict of purpose.

00:08:20.359 --> 00:08:21.679
And those are things that you can iron out.

00:08:21.679 --> 00:08:26.279
So as you are hiring in your organization, hire people that could become friends, but

00:08:26.279 --> 00:08:28.079
that you wouldn't expect to become friends.

00:08:28.079 --> 00:08:33.760
Hire people who are competent, who are smart, who are ethical, and who are interested in

00:08:33.760 --> 00:08:35.880
doing what you're doing.

00:08:35.880 --> 00:08:37.799
Onboarding is another really big thing.

00:08:38.039 --> 00:08:42.640
Just know that you have problems and then hire somebody and say, good luck, here's a

00:08:42.640 --> 00:08:49.400
third of a wiki that is aspirational and doesn't actually reflect the systems that we have

00:08:49.400 --> 00:08:52.760
and ask me questions, because they won't know what questions to ask.

00:08:52.760 --> 00:08:58.520
So have a methodical onboarding process that at least gets somebody set up for, if not

00:08:58.520 --> 00:09:01.760
the first six months, at least the first three months.

00:09:01.760 --> 00:09:05.159
And that gives them context to know what to ask.

00:09:05.159 --> 00:09:06.359
Culture is really important.

00:09:06.359 --> 00:09:13.440
So I have several friends of mine who have been killing it, and so they're now managers.

00:09:13.440 --> 00:09:17.559
And I've been doing this management thing for about five years now.

00:09:17.559 --> 00:09:19.880
So I wouldn't call myself an expert by any means.

00:09:19.880 --> 00:09:24.440
But I've made a few mistakes that I can steer them away from.

00:09:24.440 --> 00:09:28.080
And one of the things that one person came to me and said, you know, I don't like the

00:09:28.080 --> 00:09:30.239
culture that my team is developing.

00:09:30.239 --> 00:09:31.799
I don't like what's happening.

00:09:31.799 --> 00:09:38.760
And I asked him, have you tried to instill a culture, or are you just hoping that a nice

00:09:38.760 --> 00:09:40.520
culture happens?

00:09:40.520 --> 00:09:41.679
Have you guys gone out to lunch?

00:09:41.679 --> 00:09:44.479
Have you done any breaking of bread?

00:09:44.479 --> 00:09:47.200
Have you talked about things that are not work-related?

00:09:47.200 --> 00:09:54.919
Because the only way to have a really constructive and additive relationship work-wise is to

00:09:54.919 --> 00:09:56.159
have trust.

00:09:56.159 --> 00:09:59.880
And the only way to have trust is to have trust.

00:09:59.960 --> 00:10:05.400
It doesn't magically happen just because somebody signs a W-9 form.

00:10:05.400 --> 00:10:06.799
You have to work at it.

00:10:06.799 --> 00:10:09.440
You have to be intentional about it.

00:10:09.440 --> 00:10:14.840
So set up situations where you are building a team.

00:10:14.840 --> 00:10:20.919
And I'm not saying go do trust falls if you think those are ridiculous.

00:10:20.919 --> 00:10:23.679
I don't think they're ridiculous, but you may very well.

00:10:23.679 --> 00:10:28.359
But there is something that matches the culture that you're trying to build, and build it.

00:10:28.359 --> 00:10:31.440
Don't expect it to just magically take place.

00:10:31.440 --> 00:10:32.799
This is both about rules.

00:10:32.799 --> 00:10:36.559
But as we've learned politically over the last two years in this country, it's also

00:10:36.559 --> 00:10:40.960
about norms, things that aren't explicitly written out but that are important to you.

00:10:40.960 --> 00:10:44.960
Say those out loud and set those as expectations.

00:10:44.960 --> 00:10:47.799
And the last thing is diversity and inclusion.

00:10:47.799 --> 00:10:52.440
So don't just have people who went to the same schools that you did, who came from the

00:10:52.440 --> 00:10:55.799
same backgrounds that you did, who ask the same questions that you do, who understand

00:10:55.799 --> 00:10:59.960
the world as you do, who are part of the same systems as you are.

00:10:59.960 --> 00:11:09.880
So for instance, in my role, we're a consumer hardware, software, and data company.

00:11:09.880 --> 00:11:11.400
And I'm here in a personal capacity.

00:11:11.400 --> 00:11:16.239
But for those of you who don't know about me, I run data science at iRobot.

00:11:16.239 --> 00:11:23.440
And one of the really important things is what kind of household do we want having our

00:11:23.440 --> 00:11:24.840
product in it?

00:11:24.880 --> 00:11:30.280
And do we have people developing that product and thinking about that product in ways that

00:11:30.280 --> 00:11:32.280
reflect those households?

00:11:32.280 --> 00:11:33.320
Because guess what?

00:11:33.320 --> 00:11:37.200
The people who are buying our product don't all look like the people who think computer

00:11:37.200 --> 00:11:40.599
science is fun.

00:11:40.599 --> 00:11:47.280
Because otherwise, they would all be working for iRobot instead of buying iRobot products.

00:11:47.280 --> 00:11:53.960
And not just having that diversity of experience, of personality, and of thought, but including

00:11:54.320 --> 00:12:01.039
not having one person who thinks different who is now responsible for reflecting all

00:12:01.039 --> 00:12:05.559
of the nuance that come from that background.

00:12:05.559 --> 00:12:08.400
So you want to make sure that that person feels like they're part of the organization

00:12:08.400 --> 00:12:14.320
and they're not just there to represent that which the organization is not.

00:12:14.320 --> 00:12:20.119
So all this brings me back to the point of what it means to be clueless.

00:12:20.119 --> 00:12:22.840
And we are all clueless.

00:12:22.840 --> 00:12:25.359
I'm going to say that again.

00:12:25.359 --> 00:12:27.679
We're all clueless.

00:12:27.679 --> 00:12:34.400
Because there are more ways to think about things than there are atoms in the universe.

00:12:34.400 --> 00:12:36.960
This I've not read anywhere, but I am a firm believer in it.

00:12:36.960 --> 00:12:40.640
And I am only an expert in like three of them.

00:12:40.640 --> 00:12:50.440
And I am incredibly clueless about like 98,397,037,004.

00:12:50.440 --> 00:12:54.000
So how do we know that we are ready to ask the right questions?

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:55.659
Well, we're not.

00:12:55.659 --> 00:12:59.599
And I think being that vulnerable and having that humility to understand that there are

00:12:59.599 --> 00:13:02.280
things that you are going to hire for and there are things that you're not going to

00:13:02.280 --> 00:13:05.840
hire for and be mindful that those things are true.

00:13:05.840 --> 00:13:10.400
Not putting them behind a dark wall and not thinking about it and hoping for the best,

00:13:10.400 --> 00:13:17.159
but being mindful that those things will take place and learning from them.

00:13:17.159 --> 00:13:22.080
This is a chart by David Whittaker.

00:13:22.080 --> 00:13:24.840
And I think a lot of you probably have seen this before.

00:13:24.840 --> 00:13:26.679
It's about imposter syndrome.

00:13:26.679 --> 00:13:28.320
And I don't want to talk about imposter syndrome.

00:13:28.320 --> 00:13:31.400
I think this is a very valuable chart in that sense.

00:13:31.400 --> 00:13:34.799
But I want to co-opt this and take it in a different direction.

00:13:34.799 --> 00:13:37.760
Because the blue is what we know.

00:13:37.760 --> 00:13:40.059
And the yellow is what we don't know.

00:13:40.719 --> 00:13:44.059
And what this chart is saying is we tend to assume that a single person knows all of the

00:13:44.059 --> 00:13:48.619
yellow when, in fact, you have lots of people who know lots of yellows.

00:13:48.619 --> 00:13:52.760
And I think the point that I want to make is that's why you want lots of people with

00:13:52.760 --> 00:14:00.820
lots of intersecting, overlapping, but not perfectly on top of each other yellow circles.

00:14:00.820 --> 00:14:07.460
This is the reason for diversity is so that if you have a lot of people who have similar

00:14:07.460 --> 00:14:12.419
experiences, backgrounds, and expertise, there's going to be a whole host of yellows

00:14:12.419 --> 00:14:18.380
that you're never going to be aware that you should be looking at and investigating and

00:14:18.380 --> 00:14:21.859
investing in.

00:14:21.859 --> 00:14:23.700
Which leads me to this point.

00:14:23.700 --> 00:14:26.539
You should not protect your teams from failure.

00:14:26.539 --> 00:14:28.460
You should prepare them for it.

00:14:28.460 --> 00:14:31.979
Because if you have a single data scientist, there's a lot of yellow that's missing.

00:14:31.979 --> 00:14:35.020
If you have two data scientists, there's still a lot of yellow that's missing.

00:14:35.340 --> 00:14:38.179
And I'll tell you what, if you have 100 data scientists working for you, there's still

00:14:38.179 --> 00:14:40.820
a lot of yellow that you're missing.

00:14:40.820 --> 00:14:47.020
Fewer and fewer shades and sizes of yellow, hopefully, as you improve on your processes.

00:14:47.020 --> 00:14:50.500
But still, there's always going to be something that is overlooked.

00:14:50.500 --> 00:14:52.820
There's always going to be something...

00:14:52.820 --> 00:14:53.820
And you know what?

00:14:53.820 --> 00:14:54.820
Bits flip.

00:14:54.820 --> 00:14:58.340
I would not have believed unless it had happened to me personally.

00:14:58.340 --> 00:15:03.219
But things go haywire when they shouldn't have gone haywire for any other reason.

00:15:03.219 --> 00:15:04.820
Which brings me to...

00:15:04.820 --> 00:15:06.179
Should you only hire experts?

00:15:06.179 --> 00:15:07.179
No.

00:15:07.179 --> 00:15:08.179
No, no, no, no.

00:15:08.179 --> 00:15:09.460
Have tons of interns.

00:15:09.460 --> 00:15:14.020
Have tons of people who have never done this before, and this is their first foray into

00:15:14.020 --> 00:15:15.020
data science.

00:15:15.020 --> 00:15:21.140
Because the luxury of ignorance is that these folks who are extremely junior don't know

00:15:21.140 --> 00:15:23.219
what they should know.

00:15:23.219 --> 00:15:27.059
They don't have any of the assumptions that are subliminal and are baked into the way

00:15:27.059 --> 00:15:29.900
that we think, because it's the way we've always thought.

00:15:29.900 --> 00:15:33.340
Because the world moves, but our assumptions tend to be sedimented.

00:15:33.340 --> 00:15:38.460
And so as you bring in new talent, they know to question things that you've forgotten to

00:15:38.460 --> 00:15:40.580
question again.

00:15:40.580 --> 00:15:46.940
The other thing that I would recommend, if nobody has read the book Chaos Monkeys, about

00:15:46.940 --> 00:15:53.979
the resilience of systems at Netflix and how there are systems that are turned off on purpose

00:15:53.979 --> 00:15:59.200
just to make sure that things can still function when part of the system goes down.

00:15:59.200 --> 00:16:01.359
This is true for people.

00:16:01.359 --> 00:16:04.760
Maternity leave, paternity leave, vacation.

00:16:04.760 --> 00:16:08.840
Your business should continue to function if somebody needs to go to a conference.

00:16:08.840 --> 00:16:10.039
So you should allow it.

00:16:10.039 --> 00:16:16.400
You should foster that kind of mentality, and you should use it as a test for the resilience

00:16:16.400 --> 00:16:18.700
of your own organization.

00:16:18.700 --> 00:16:21.440
So I'll close with a couple of thoughts.

00:16:21.440 --> 00:16:23.880
Where should this new team live?

00:16:23.880 --> 00:16:27.599
I mean, if you're a single data scientist, you're probably embedded in a part of some

00:16:27.719 --> 00:16:29.280
organization, but where should it live?

00:16:29.280 --> 00:16:31.520
I've been doing this for many, many years.

00:16:31.520 --> 00:16:33.599
I'm not going to tell you how many years.

00:16:33.599 --> 00:16:35.599
I have really great skin care.

00:16:35.599 --> 00:16:39.039
But it doesn't matter.

00:16:39.039 --> 00:16:40.039
It really doesn't matter.

00:16:40.039 --> 00:16:44.280
And I'm happy to get into a Twitter conversation about this with somebody who disagrees with

00:16:44.280 --> 00:16:45.280
me.

00:16:45.280 --> 00:16:48.679
Because I have worked in data science within the finance organization.

00:16:48.679 --> 00:16:53.239
Financial operations, IT, engineering, R&D, software.

00:16:53.239 --> 00:16:57.239
And if you're doing good work, and you're solving problems, and you're having people

00:16:57.239 --> 00:17:02.159
address these problems in new, innovative, creative, and competent ways, this is the

00:17:02.159 --> 00:17:03.320
least of your problems.

00:17:03.320 --> 00:17:06.719
And usually this is where everybody gets hung up.

00:17:06.719 --> 00:17:11.680
Because when you're going from one to many, the importance is not the nodes.

00:17:11.680 --> 00:17:13.400
The importance is the edges.

00:17:13.400 --> 00:17:20.520
The importance is how people, humans, communicate and interact.

00:17:20.520 --> 00:17:25.359
And that's where a lot of the knowledge that you're leveraging in your organization comes

00:17:25.359 --> 00:17:27.160
from.

00:17:27.160 --> 00:17:30.319
But the thing to remember is teams don't scale.

00:17:30.319 --> 00:17:35.239
And so once you reach a sort of critical mass where you're not being able to have that trust

00:17:35.239 --> 00:17:41.000
anymore, because those edges are frayed and stretched, it's time for a new team.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:45.040
And at that point, you add specialization, and you add process, and you add resilience

00:17:45.040 --> 00:17:48.280
again.

00:17:48.280 --> 00:17:52.800
If you've seen me talk before, A, you know that I give the caveat about my voice breaking

00:17:52.800 --> 00:17:53.800
every time.

00:17:53.800 --> 00:17:58.160
But you've also seen me talk about dynasties and intellectual inbreeding, and there's a

00:17:58.160 --> 00:18:03.920
reason why the royal families of 15th century Europe looked the way that they did.

00:18:03.920 --> 00:18:08.000
There's also meritocracies and survivorship bias, and just because you made it doesn't

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:10.160
mean that that's the only way to make it.

00:18:10.160 --> 00:18:12.959
And lastly, I don't know if anybody here has heard about super chickens.

00:18:12.959 --> 00:18:16.239
But if you haven't, come find me after, because it's a really cool story.

00:18:16.640 --> 00:18:21.520
In essence, when you take a whole bunch of chickens that are amazing at what they do,

00:18:21.520 --> 00:18:22.520
they kill each other.

00:18:22.520 --> 00:18:26.680
They don't make each other better.

00:18:26.680 --> 00:18:29.359
Because excellence isn't binary.

00:18:29.359 --> 00:18:30.719
Excellence varies.

00:18:30.719 --> 00:18:35.760
And your job as you build out teams is to foster an environment where people can be

00:18:35.760 --> 00:18:41.439
excellent, but where they have the psychological safety to not have to be excellent.

00:18:41.439 --> 00:18:43.079
And they'll surprise you.

00:18:43.079 --> 00:18:46.199
And so with that, I know I'm the thing between you and lunch.

00:18:46.199 --> 00:18:47.199
So thank you very much.

00:18:47.199 --> 00:18:50.079
And if you have any questions, I'm happy to answer.

00:18:50.079 --> 00:18:59.560
Now we have time for a couple of quick questions for Angela, if you have any.

00:18:59.560 --> 00:19:01.560
We still have the mics around.

00:19:08.839 --> 00:19:10.839
Oh, a couple of questions.

00:19:10.839 --> 00:19:11.839
Hi.

00:19:11.839 --> 00:19:12.839
Thanks for the presentation.

00:19:12.839 --> 00:19:13.839
It was great.

00:19:13.839 --> 00:19:14.839
Thank you.

00:19:14.880 --> 00:19:20.040
So what is your team, and how long did it take you to assemble it to where it is today?

00:19:20.040 --> 00:19:28.479
So for confidentiality reasons, I can't disclose too much about specifically how iRobot is

00:19:28.479 --> 00:19:30.599
organized and does its business.

00:19:30.599 --> 00:19:33.560
But I can talk in generalities, and you're smart enough that you can read in between

00:19:33.560 --> 00:19:34.560
the lines.

00:19:34.560 --> 00:19:40.920
So I think the teams that I have managed and built that are most successful tend to have

00:19:40.920 --> 00:19:50.319
about five to 10 data scientists of all walks, junior to senior, and about three data engineers

00:19:50.319 --> 00:19:56.560
to start is a really good size.

00:19:56.560 --> 00:20:04.000
And this is for a $2 to $5 billion market cap company, for context.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:05.079
Hi.

00:20:05.079 --> 00:20:09.640
If you are currently the only data scientist within an organization, and you are doing

00:20:09.640 --> 00:20:15.280
all of the things, how do you make that business case that you need to bring in more people

00:20:15.280 --> 00:20:20.880
if you're already getting beyond the budget discussion of hiring more people?

00:20:20.880 --> 00:20:25.319
How do you make that case without just stopping doing one of the pieces and saying you need

00:20:25.319 --> 00:20:27.800
someone else to do it now?

00:20:27.800 --> 00:20:33.000
The best way that I have found to make that case is to highlight the opportunity cost

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:35.119
of not doing it.

00:20:35.119 --> 00:20:41.160
If you're only saying how much it'll cost and how good it'll be, that's one avenue,

00:20:41.160 --> 00:20:43.319
but that only gets you half of the way there.

00:20:43.319 --> 00:20:48.000
I think the important thing to highlight is by not doing this, this is the revenue we're

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:52.400
foregoing because that number is going to be much bigger.

00:20:52.400 --> 00:20:54.760
Here are the insights that we are failing to see.

00:20:54.760 --> 00:20:56.599
Here's where burnout is taking us.

00:20:56.599 --> 00:21:01.680
Here is how we've gotten to a point where the scope of the responsibility is so big

00:21:01.800 --> 00:21:09.040
that we're doing the minimum viable solution, and so those systems are not resilient.

00:21:09.040 --> 00:21:15.680
The likelihood, the risk-adjusted value of that decision, if a catastrophic event were

00:21:15.680 --> 00:21:20.040
to happen, is taking the systems down for X many weeks, and that's the cost of that.

00:21:20.040 --> 00:21:26.560
So highlighting the cost of not expanding when it's evident that an expansion is warranted,

00:21:26.560 --> 00:21:34.319
to me, has been a more fruitful conversation and has led to better results, for Angela's

00:21:34.319 --> 00:21:39.880
definition of better, than highlighting what the cost would be for an extra FTE.

00:21:39.880 --> 00:21:43.160
I think we have one more quick one here.

00:21:43.160 --> 00:21:49.319
How much butch back do you get on these ideas, and who would freak out the most?

00:21:49.319 --> 00:21:53.760
That's a really interesting question.

00:21:53.760 --> 00:21:55.479
There's two ways to answer that.

00:21:55.479 --> 00:22:04.199
I am privileged in that I get to choose to work for people who agree with my management

00:22:04.199 --> 00:22:07.920
philosophy, so how much pushback do I get?

00:22:07.920 --> 00:22:14.160
I don't get pushback because I filter employers out who would have given me pushback, so I'm

00:22:14.160 --> 00:22:21.260
very transparent in the interviewing process for myself to not get myself into that situation.

00:22:21.260 --> 00:22:26.260
Not everybody has that, and there is substantial pushback, especially in organizations that

00:22:26.260 --> 00:22:33.939
look homogenous, so not everybody can choose not to work there, but I have also found that

00:22:33.939 --> 00:22:42.420
making the argument monetary reduces the amount of friction, so if you say, and I'm not saying

00:22:42.420 --> 00:22:48.859
this happens at iRobot because I filtered that out, but were I to say we are building

00:22:48.859 --> 00:22:58.099
robots for software developers, we're not building robots for homemakers, for people

00:22:58.099 --> 00:23:03.540
who want to maintain a home, and so we're making decisions about how these robots operate

00:23:03.540 --> 00:23:08.060
that don't match the pain points of the people who would be paying us for these robots.

00:23:08.060 --> 00:23:15.020
Again, this is not true, but that's the kind of argument that can help open up eyes for

00:23:15.020 --> 00:23:19.859
people who see it monetarily as foregoing revenue.

